autophagic control of intracellular Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Immunity (in the press). 87. Taylor, G. A., Feng, C. G. & Sher, A. p47 GTPases: regulators of immunity to intracellular pathogens. Nature Rev. Immunol. 4, 100–109 (2004). 88. Levine, B. & Yuan, J. Autophagy in cell death: an innocent convict? J. Clin. Invest. 115, 2679–2688 (2005). 89. Yoshimori, T. Autophagy: paying Charon’s toll. Cell 128, 833–836 (2007). 90. Espert, L. et al. Autophagy is involved in T cell death after binding of HIV-1 envelope proteins to CXCR4. J. Clin. Invest. 116, 2161–2172 (2006). 91. Maderna, P. & Godson, C. Phagocytosis of apoptotic cells and the resolution of inflammation. Biochim. Biophys. Acta 1639, 141–151 (2003). 92. Grossmayer, G. E. et al. Removal of dying cells and systemic lupus erythematosus. Mod. Rheumatol. 15, 383–390 (2005). 93. Gaipl, U. S. et al. Inefficient clearance of dying cells and autoreactivity. Curr. Top. Microbiol. Immunol. 305, 161–176 (2006). 94. Sartor, R. S. Mechanisms of disease pathogenesis: pathogenesis of Crohn’s disease and ulcerative colitis. Nature Clin. Pract. Gastroenterol. Hepatol. 3, 390–407 (2006). 95. Baumgart, D. C. & Carding, S. R. Inflammatory bowel disease: cause and immunobiology. Lancet 369, 1627–1640 (2007). 96. Xu, Y. et al. Toll-like receptor 4 is a sensor for autophagy associated with innate immunity. Immunity 27, 135–144 (2007).

